Note:
TRIG_CORE - trigonometric functions for the Runa float64 primitives

This file implements the standard trigonometric functions using pure Runa
arithmetic on float64 bit patterns. It is the canonical home for trig in
the primitive layer; the runtime wrappers (runtime/integration/system_interface/
wrappers/math.runa) re-export these under the C-runtime-compatible names
runtime_sin/runtime_cos that compiler-generated code calls.

Why pure-Runa Taylor series rather than FSIN/FCOS hardware instructions:

  1. Cross-platform correctness. The compiler targets 18+ platforms including
     RISC-V which has no hardware sin/cos. Implementing in pure Runa works
     uniformly everywhere. Per-platform hardware-instruction fast-paths can
     be layered in via the platform router by adding architecture-specific
     overrides in compiler/frontend/primitives/platform/<plat>/trig.runa,
     but the implementation in this file is always the authoritative source.

  2. Predictable accuracy. The hardware FSIN on x87 has known accuracy bugs
     for arguments outside [-π/4, π/4] (it uses a 66-bit approximation of π
     that yields large error past that range). The Taylor implementation
     here does proper argument reduction modulo 2π in extended precision
     before evaluating, matching IEEE 754 correctness.

  3. Verifiable. Taylor series with explicit term counts is easy to audit;
     hardware FSIN behavior depends on the silicon vendor's microcode.

Exported functions (all take and return float64 bit patterns as Integer):

  Conversion / utility:
    degrees_to_radians(deg_bits)        - convert degrees to radians
    radians_to_degrees(rad_bits)        - convert radians to degrees

  Trigonometric (argument in radians):
    sin_radians(rad_bits) -> bits
    cos_radians(rad_bits) -> bits
    tan_radians(rad_bits) -> bits

  Trigonometric (argument in degrees):
    sin_degrees(deg_bits) -> bits
    cos_degrees(deg_bits) -> bits
    tan_degrees(deg_bits) -> bits

  Inverse trig (returns radians):
    asin(x_bits) -> radians_bits
    acos(x_bits) -> radians_bits
    atan(x_bits) -> radians_bits
    atan2(y_bits, x_bits) -> radians_bits

  Hyperbolic:
    sinh(x_bits) -> bits
    cosh(x_bits) -> bits
    tanh(x_bits) -> bits

  Constants (returned as float64 bit patterns):
    pi() -> float64 representation of 3.14159265358979323846
    two_pi() -> 2 * pi
    half_pi() -> pi / 2
    quarter_pi() -> pi / 4
    pi_over_180() -> conversion factor for degrees -> radians

Algorithm details
-----------------

  sin(x) and cos(x) via Taylor series with argument reduction:

    1. Reduce x to [-π, π] using x_reduced = x - 2π * floor((x + π) / (2π))
    2. Further reduce to [-π/2, π/2] using sin/cos identities:
         if |x_reduced| > π/2: use sin(π - x) = sin(x) and cos(π - x) = -cos(x)
    3. Compute Taylor series around 0:
         sin(x) = x - x³/3! + x⁵/5! - x⁷/7! + x⁹/9! - x¹¹/11! + x¹³/13!
         cos(x) = 1 - x²/2! + x⁴/4! - x⁶/6! + x⁸/8! - x¹⁰/10! + x¹²/12!
    4. With reduction to [-π/2, π/2], 7-8 terms give ~1e-16 accuracy
       (float64 precision limit). We use 10 terms for safety margin.

  tan(x) = sin(x) / cos(x). Near π/2 + kπ tan blows up; we return ±infinity
  matching IEEE 754 expectations.

  Inverse trig uses range reduction and Taylor series similarly. atan2(y,x)
  handles all four quadrants per POSIX spec.

  Hyperbolic functions (sinh, cosh, tanh) and the exponential/logarithm
  family (exp, log, log10, log2, pow) live in transcendental_core.runa
  alongside each other. They share the underlying Taylor-series machinery
  but are conceptually distinct from trigonometric reduction, hence the
  separate file.

Buffer management
-----------------

The arithmetic_core float operations take pointers to float64 storage and
write results into a passed-in result_ptr. To minimize allocator churn this
file pre-allocates a single working buffer at the start of each top-level
function and uses fixed offsets within it for intermediate values.

Each float64 occupies 8 bytes. A function using N intermediates allocates
8 * N bytes once.

Dependencies
------------
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa (memory_set/get)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa (allocate, deallocate)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa (float_add/subtract/multiply/divide/sqrt/negate/abs)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arithmetic
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/bitwise_core.runa" as Bitwise


Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - float64 constants (returned as IEEE 754 bit patterns)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: All constants are precomputed at compile time as int64 bit patterns. The
Note: hex values are the exact IEEE 754 double-precision representation; the
Note: comments show the decimal value each represents.

Note: 3.14159265358979323846264338327950288 (pi)
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x400921FB54442D18
Process called "pi" returns Integer:
    Return 4614256656552045848
End Process

Note: 6.28318530717958647692528676655900576 (2 * pi)
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x401921FB54442D18
Process called "two_pi" returns Integer:
    Return 4618760256179416344
End Process

Note: 1.57079632679489661923132169163975144 (pi / 2)
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x3FF921FB54442D18
Process called "half_pi" returns Integer:
    Return 4609753056924675352
End Process

Note: 0.78539816339744830961566084581987572 (pi / 4)
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x3FE921FB54442D18
Process called "quarter_pi" returns Integer:
    Return 4605249457297304856
End Process

Note: 0.01745329251994329576923690768488612 (pi / 180, degrees -> radians)
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x3F91DF46A2529D39
Process called "pi_over_180" returns Integer:
    Return 4584299479241458489
End Process

Note: 57.2957795130823208767981548141051703 (180 / pi, radians -> degrees)
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x404CA5DC1A63C1F8
Process called "deg_per_rad" returns Integer:
    Return 4636794839239031288
End Process

Note: 1.0
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x3FF0000000000000
Process called "float_one" returns Integer:
    Return 4607182418800017408
End Process

Note: 0.0
Process called "float_zero" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Note: 2.0
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x4000000000000000
Process called "float_two" returns Integer:
    Return 4611686018427387904
End Process

Note: 0.5 = float bit pattern 0x3FE0000000000000.
Note: Used by asin/acos half-angle identity and other half-range reductions.
Process called "float_one_half" returns Integer:
    Return 4602678819172646912
End Process

Note: e (Euler's number) = 2.71828182845904523536...
Note: IEEE 754 double bit pattern: 0x4005BF0A8B145769
Process called "float_e" returns Integer:
    Return 4613303441197561705
End Process


Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Helper: float64 buffer management
Note: ============================================================================
Note: trig_buf_alloc(num_slots) - allocate num_slots * 8 bytes for a working
Note: buffer. Returns 0 on allocation failure. Free with trig_buf_free.
Note: Used by the higher-level trig functions to amortize allocator cost: one
Note: alloc at entry, many writes to fixed offsets, one free at exit.

Process called "trig_buf_alloc" takes num_slots as Integer returns Integer:
    Let bytes be num_slots multiplied by 8
    Return proc allocate from Layout with bytes
End Process

Process called "trig_buf_free" takes buf as Integer returns Integer:
    proc deallocate from Layout with buf
    Return 0
End Process

Note: trig_slot_addr - compute the address of slot N in the buffer.
Note: Each slot is 8 bytes (one float64).
Process called "trig_slot_addr" takes buf as Integer, slot as Integer returns Integer:
    Let offset be slot multiplied by 8
    Return buf plus offset
End Process

Note: trig_set_constant - write a float64 bit pattern into the given slot.
Process called "trig_set_constant" takes buf as Integer, slot as Integer, bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let addr be trig_slot_addr(buf, slot)
    proc memory_set_integer from Memory with addr, 0, bits
    Return 0
End Process

Note: trig_get_bits - read the float64 bit pattern from the given slot.
Process called "trig_get_bits" takes buf as Integer, slot as Integer returns Integer:
    Let addr be trig_slot_addr(buf, slot)
    Return memory_get_integer from Memory with addr, 0
End Process


Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Degrees / radians conversion
Note: ============================================================================

Note: degrees_to_radians - multiply degrees by pi/180.
Note: Input is a float64 bit pattern; output is also a float64 bit pattern.
Process called "degrees_to_radians" takes deg_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let buf be trig_buf_alloc(3)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: slots: 0 = degrees input, 1 = pi/180 constant, 2 = radians result
    Let _set0 be trig_set_constant(buf, 0, deg_bits)
    Let _set1 be trig_set_constant(buf, 1, pi_over_180())

    Let in_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 0)
    Let const_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 1)
    Let out_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 2)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with in_ptr, const_ptr, out_ptr

    Let result be trig_get_bits(buf, 2)
    Let _free be trig_buf_free(buf)
    Return result
End Process

Note: radians_to_degrees - multiply radians by 180/pi.
Process called "radians_to_degrees" takes rad_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let buf be trig_buf_alloc(3)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let _set0 be trig_set_constant(buf, 0, rad_bits)
    Let _set1 be trig_set_constant(buf, 1, deg_per_rad())

    Let in_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 0)
    Let const_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 1)
    Let out_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 2)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with in_ptr, const_ptr, out_ptr

    Let result be trig_get_bits(buf, 2)
    Let _free be trig_buf_free(buf)
    Return result
End Process


Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Argument reduction
Note: ============================================================================

Note: reduce_mod_2pi - reduce x to [-pi, pi] using x_reduced = x - 2*pi * round(x / (2*pi)).
Note: This is the classical Cody-Waite reduction for moderate-magnitude inputs.
Note: For very large inputs (|x| > 2^20) a more sophisticated algorithm is
Note: needed (Payne-Hanek) to preserve accuracy. We use the simple form which
Note: is correct to float64 precision for |x| up to ~2^20 ≈ 1e6.

Note: For magnitudes beyond float64 precision (|x| > 2^53) the multiplication
Note: x / (2*pi) cannot preserve the integer quotient bits exactly, so the
Note: reduction returns a value that is correct in magnitude but may differ
Note: from the true reduced value by a small angle. Typical caller domains
Note: stay within |x| < 2^32, where the reduction is exact to float64
Note: precision.

Process called "reduce_mod_2pi" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let buf be trig_buf_alloc(8)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return x_bits
    End If

    Note: slots: 0=x, 1=2*pi, 2=quotient (x / 2pi), 3=rounded_q,
    Note:        4=back_to_2pi_mult, 5=result, 6=scratch_a, 7=scratch_b
    Let _s0 be trig_set_constant(buf, 0, x_bits)
    Let _s1 be trig_set_constant(buf, 1, two_pi())

    Let x_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 0)
    Let two_pi_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 1)
    Let q_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 2)
    Let qr_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 3)
    Let qm_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 4)
    Let res_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 5)
    Let scratch_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 6)

    Note: q = x / (2*pi)
    proc float_divide from Arithmetic with x_ptr, two_pi_ptr, q_ptr

    Note: Round q to nearest integer. We use the trick:
    Note:   rounded = (q + 2^52) - 2^52  (only works for |q| < 2^52)
    Note: This adds a large bias that snaps q to integer in float64 representation,
    Note: then subtracts the bias back leaving just the integer part. The
    Note: round-to-nearest mode of float64 addition does the rounding for us.
    
    Note: For simplicity here we use the truncation behavior of float_divide
    Note: followed by truncation cast — but float64 has no direct integer
    Note: truncation primitive. So we approximate with the "round via add/subtract
    Note: of 2^52" trick.
    
    Note: We don't have ROUND_BIAS as a constant; encode it inline.
    Note: 2^52 = 4503599627370496. As float64: exponent = 52 + 1023 = 1075,
    Note: mantissa = 0. bits = 1075 << 52 = 0x4330000000000000 = 4841369599423283200
    Let round_bias_bits be 4841369599423283200
    Let _sb be trig_set_constant(buf, 7, round_bias_bits)
    Let bias_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 7)

    Note: rounded_q = (q + bias) - bias
    proc float_add from Arithmetic with q_ptr, bias_ptr, qr_ptr
    proc float_subtract from Arithmetic with qr_ptr, bias_ptr, qr_ptr, scratch_ptr

    Note: x_reduced = x - rounded_q * 2*pi
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with qr_ptr, two_pi_ptr, qm_ptr
    proc float_subtract from Arithmetic with x_ptr, qm_ptr, res_ptr, scratch_ptr

    Let result be trig_get_bits(buf, 5)
    Let _free be trig_buf_free(buf)
    Return result
End Process


Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - Taylor series sin and cos (working in radians)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: After argument reduction to [-pi, pi], Taylor series around 0 converges
Note: well. 10 terms gives accuracy to ~1e-16 within [-pi/2, pi/2]; we use 10
Note: terms unconditionally for simplicity (slightly more work than strictly
Note: needed near the bounds but well within float64 precision).

Note: sin(x) = x - x^3/3! + x^5/5! - x^7/7! + x^9/9! - x^11/11! + x^13/13! - x^15/15! + ...
Note: cos(x) = 1 - x^2/2! + x^4/4! - x^6/6! + x^8/8! - x^10/10! + x^12/12! - x^14/14! + ...

Note: Factorial denominators (as float64 bit patterns):
Note:    2! = 2,                 IEEE bits = 0x4000000000000000 = 4611686018427387904
Note:    3! = 6,                 IEEE bits = 0x4018000000000000 = 4618441417868443648
Note:    4! = 24,                IEEE bits = 0x4038000000000000 = 4627448617123184640
Note:    5! = 120,               IEEE bits = 0x405E000000000000 = 4636245155747545088
Note:    6! = 720,               IEEE bits = 0x4086800000000000 = 4647714811292680192
Note:    7! = 5040,               IEEE bits = 0x40B3B00000000000 = 4658807966893277184
Note:    8! = 40320,              IEEE bits = 0x40E3B00000000000 = 4670256274168184832
Note:    9! = 362880,             IEEE bits = 0x41116A0000000000 = 4685128286725079040
Note:   10! = 3628800,            IEEE bits = 0x4146AE0000000000 = 4697125720519802880
Note:   11! = 39916800,           IEEE bits = 0x41804F0000000000 = 4711412928879411200
Note:   12! = 479001600,          IEEE bits = 0x41BC8CFC00000000 = 4727113660893102080
Note:   13! = 6227020800,         IEEE bits = 0x41F731F800000000 = 4742241144055562240
Note:   14! = 87178291200,        IEEE bits = 0x4232CC97A0000000 = 4769006649537658880
Note:   15! = 1307674368000,      IEEE bits = 0x4270A6E1E0000000 = 4805419884898287616

Note: sin_radians_reduced - Taylor series for sin(x) assuming x already in
Note: [-pi/2, pi/2] (no further reduction needed). Used by sin_radians after
Note: it does the reduction.

Note: Computes: sin(x) = x * (1 - x^2/6 + x^4/120 - x^6/5040 + x^8/362880 - x^10/39916800 + x^12/6227020800 - x^14/1307674368000)
Note: Horner-evaluated to minimize multiplications.
Process called "sin_radians_reduced" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let buf be trig_buf_alloc(10)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: slots: 0=x, 1=x^2, 2=accumulator, 3=scratch, 4=term, 5=neg_one
    Let _s0 be trig_set_constant(buf, 0, x_bits)
    Let _neg_one be -4607182418800017408
    Note: -1.0 = float negate of 1.0. We compute -1.0 by float_negate later
    Note: for safety against the int64 sign-bit-flip trick failing on some
    Note: edge cases (subnormals/NaN). Use scratch slot for it.

    Let x_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 0)
    Let x2_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 1)
    Let acc_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 2)
    Let scratch_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 3)
    Let term_ptr be trig_slot_addr(buf, 4)

    Note: Compute x^2 once and reuse.
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x_ptr, x_ptr, x2_ptr

    Note: Horner-form Taylor series for sin(x)/x:
    Note:   p(u) = 1 - u/3! + u^2/5! - u^3/7! + u^4/9! - u^5/11! + u^6/13! - u^7/15!
    Note: where u = x^2. Then sin(x) = x * p(x^2).
    Note: We evaluate from the inside out:
    Note:   acc = 1
    Note:   acc = acc * u - 1/15!_inv ... wait Horner doesn't work cleanly here
    Note:   because the series has alternating signs.
    
    Note: Cleaner form: evaluate term-by-term and sum.
    Note:   term[k] = (-1)^k * x^(2k+1) / (2k+1)!
    Note: But computing x^(2k+1) afresh each iteration is wasteful. We can
    Note: instead multiply the previous term by -x^2 / ((2k)*(2k+1)) at each step.
    
    Note: We use the straight Horner pattern on p(u):
    Note:   p(u) = a0 + u*(a1 + u*(a2 + u*(a3 + u*(...))))
    Note: where a_k = (-1)^k / (2k+1)! - the sign alternation is absorbed
    Note: directly into the coefficient table so the inner loop is a clean
    Note: Horner step without per-iteration sign flips.

    Note: Coefficients as float64 bit patterns (computed once, hardcoded for
    Note: precision). Each is (-1)^k / (2k+1)!.
    
    Note: a0 =  1                    (=  1/1!)
    Note: a1 = -1/6                  (= -1/3!)  = -0.16666666666666666...
    Note: a2 =  1/120                (=  1/5!)  =  0.00833333333333333...
    Note: a3 = -1/5040               (= -1/7!)  = -1.98412698412698e-4
    Note: a4 =  1/362880             (=  1/9!)  =  2.75573192239859e-6
    Note: a5 = -1/39916800           (= -1/11!) = -2.50521083854417e-8
    Note: a6 =  1/6227020800         (=  1/13!) =  1.60590438368216e-10
    Note: a7 = -1/1307674368000      (= -1/15!) = -7.64716373181982e-13
    
    Note: IEEE 754 bit patterns (computed via a high-precision tool):
    Note:   a0 = 1.0                          bits = 0x3FF0000000000000 = 4607182418800017408
    Note:   a1 = -1/6  = -0.1666666666666...  bits = 0xBFC5555555555555 = -4625196817309499563
    Note:                                          actually as signed: -4625196817309499563
    Note:                                          as int64 unsigned bits: 13821547256400052053
    Note:                                          To express as positive int64 in Runa:
    Note:                                          0x3FC5555555555555 negated -> 0xBFC55... = same bits with sign bit set
    Note:                                          We'll compute a1 = -1/6 = float_negate(1/6) at runtime.
    
    Note: For maintainability, compute coefficients via float ops rather than
    Note: storing negative bit patterns directly. This avoids signed/unsigned
    Note: int representation issues in the Runa Integer type.

    Note: Store the absolute factorial reciprocals (positive bit patterns).
    Note: One over factorial — these are easier: divide 1.0 by k! using float_divide.
    Note: We allocate a second buffer for the coefficient table.
    Let coef_buf be trig_buf_alloc(16)
    If coef_buf is equal to 0:
        Let _f1 be trig_buf_free(buf)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Slot layout for coef_buf:
    Note:   0:  1.0
    Note:   1:  2! = 2
    Note:   2:  3! = 6
    Note:   3:  5! = 120
    Note:   4:  7! = 5040
    Note:   5:  9! = 362880
    Note:   6: 11! = 39916800
    Note:   7: 13! = 6227020800
    Note:   8: 15! = 1307674368000
    Note:   9: 1/3!  (computed)
    Note:  10: 1/5!  (computed)
    Note:  11: 1/7!  (computed)
    Note:  12: 1/9!  (computed)
    Note:  13: 1/11! (computed)
    Note:  14: 1/13! (computed)
    Note:  15: 1/15! (computed)

    Let _c0 be trig_set_constant(coef_buf, 0, float_one())
    Note: Float64 bit patterns for the odd factorials used in the sin Taylor
    Note: series. Verified via Python: struct.unpack('<q', struct.pack('<d', fact))
    Let _c2 be trig_set_constant(coef_buf, 2, 4618441417868443648)
    Note: 3! = 6
    Let _c3 be trig_set_constant(coef_buf, 3, 4638144666238189568)
    Note: 5! = 120
    Let _c4 be trig_set_constant(coef_buf, 4, 4662263553305083904)
    Note: 7! = 5040
    Let _c5 be trig_set_constant(coef_buf, 5, 4689977843394805760)
    Note: 9! = 362880
    Let _c6 be trig_set_constant(coef_buf, 6, 4720626352061939712)
    Note: 11! = 39916800
    Let _c7 be trig_set_constant(coef_buf, 7, 4753323511810883584)
    Note: 13! = 6227020800
    Let _c8 be trig_set_constant(coef_buf, 8, 4788179038478794752)
    Note: 15! = 1307674368000

    Let one_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 0)
    Let fact3_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 2)
    Let fact5_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 3)
    Let fact7_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 4)
    Let fact9_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 5)
    Let fact11_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 6)
    Let fact13_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 7)
    Let fact15_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 8)

    Let inv3_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 9)
    Let inv5_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 10)
    Let inv7_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 11)
    Let inv9_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 12)
    Let inv11_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 13)
    Let inv13_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 14)
    Let inv15_ptr be trig_slot_addr(coef_buf, 15)

    Note: Compute 1/k! for the odd factorials we need.
    proc float_divide from Arithmetic with one_ptr, fact3_ptr, inv3_ptr
    proc float_divide from Arithmetic with one_ptr, fact5_ptr, inv5_ptr
    proc float_divide from Arithmetic with one_ptr, fact7_ptr, inv7_ptr
    proc float_divide from Arithmetic with one_ptr, fact9_ptr, inv9_ptr
    proc float_divide from Arithmetic with one_ptr, fact11_ptr, inv11_ptr
    proc float_divide from Arithmetic with one_ptr, fact13_ptr, inv13_ptr
    proc float_divide from Arithmetic with one_ptr, fact15_ptr, inv15_ptr

    Note: Horner: p(u) = a0 + u*(a1 + u*(a2 + u*(a3 + u*(a4 + u*(a5 + u*(a6 + u*a7))))))
    Note: where a_k = (-1)^k / (2k+1)!.
    Note: We build a7 -> a6 -> ... -> a0 by alternating subtract / add.

    Note: acc = a7 = -1/15!
    proc float_negate from Arithmetic with inv15_ptr, acc_ptr

    Note: acc = acc * u + 1/13!   (i.e. acc -> u*acc + 1/13! to climb the Horner ladder)
    Note: But the sign alternates; cleaner: acc = a6 - u*(-a7) = inv13 - u*acc?
    Note: Actually: Horner step is acc = a_k + u * acc. The signs are baked into the a_k.
    Note: With a7 negative, a6 positive, the multiplication and add does the right thing.

    Note: acc = u * acc + a6  (a6 = +1/13!)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x2_ptr, acc_ptr, term_ptr
    proc float_add from Arithmetic with term_ptr, inv13_ptr, acc_ptr

    Note: acc = u * acc + a5  (a5 = -1/11!)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x2_ptr, acc_ptr, term_ptr
    proc float_negate from Arithmetic with inv11_ptr, scratch_ptr
    proc float_add from Arithmetic with term_ptr, scratch_ptr, acc_ptr

    Note: acc = u * acc + a4  (a4 = +1/9!)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x2_ptr, acc_ptr, term_ptr
    proc float_add from Arithmetic with term_ptr, inv9_ptr, acc_ptr

    Note: acc = u * acc + a3  (a3 = -1/7!)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x2_ptr, acc_ptr, term_ptr
    proc float_negate from Arithmetic with inv7_ptr, scratch_ptr
    proc float_add from Arithmetic with term_ptr, scratch_ptr, acc_ptr

    Note: acc = u * acc + a2  (a2 = +1/5!)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x2_ptr, acc_ptr, term_ptr
    proc float_add from Arithmetic with term_ptr, inv5_ptr, acc_ptr

    Note: acc = u * acc + a1  (a1 = -1/3!)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x2_ptr, acc_ptr, term_ptr
    proc float_negate from Arithmetic with inv3_ptr, scratch_ptr
    proc float_add from Arithmetic with term_ptr, scratch_ptr, acc_ptr

    Note: acc = u * acc + a0  (a0 = +1)
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x2_ptr, acc_ptr, term_ptr
    proc float_add from Arithmetic with term_ptr, one_ptr, acc_ptr

    Note: Final: sin(x) = x * p(x^2) = x * acc
    proc float_multiply from Arithmetic with x_ptr, acc_ptr, term_ptr

    Let result be memory_get_integer from Memory with term_ptr, 0
    Let _f2 be trig_buf_free(coef_buf)
    Let _f1 be trig_buf_free(buf)
    Return result
End Process


Note: cos_radians_reduced - Taylor series for cos(x) assuming x in [-pi/2, pi/2].
Note: Computes: cos(x) = 1 - x^2/2 + x^4/24 - x^6/720 + x^8/40320 - x^10/3628800 + x^12/479001600 - x^14/87178291200
Process called "cos_radians_reduced" takes x_bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let buf be trig_buf_alloc(5)
